Anonymous Thu 25 Jun 2020 22:11:48 No.31129878 Report
Quoted By: >>31129889 >>31130929 >>31131466
Arctic foxes are a small fox species native to the Arctic. They are best known for their thick white/blue-grey winter coat. They are thought to have originated from Tibet.

Arctic foxes migrate during the winter, and have been known to travel great distances. In July 2019, the Norwegian Polar Institute reported about a vixen going from Norway to Canada in 76 days. Her tracker lost connection afterwards.

Their winter coat allows them to survive comfortably in sub-zero temperatures. They do not start shivering until it reaches -70 degrees Celsius. In addition, they are the only canid to have fur covering their paws. They are rather compact: having a shorter muzzle, ears, and legs than the red fox. They also have more rounded ears than the red fox. Due to this, less of their body is exposed and less heat escapes. The color of their coat also allows them to blend into the snow. Their coat changes in the summer. They shed much of their fur to adapt to the hotter climate and their fur color becomes brown or grey. Their summer coat helps to blend into the summer tundra. They do not hibernate.

Their diet consists primarily of small animals, eggs, and carcasses. It can also include berries, seaweed, and insects. They have keen senses which allow them to find lemmings underground in the snow. They also shadow polar bears and feed off of their abandoned carrion. When food is abundant, they bury it for later.

They make much of the same calls that red foxes have. They also growl and bark, which are sounds I haven’t heard red foxes making (or at least not often).

Quoted By: >>31129965 >>31130027 >>31130119 >>31130929 >>31131466

They form monogamous pairs to breed. They stay to raise the young in large complex underground dens, often with many entrances. These dens can exist for hundreds of years and can span many fox generations. Amount of kits can vary depending on the region. Packs of non-breeding foxes of both sexes can form to protect territory and the kits. When predators and prey are abundant, foxes of both sex can be promiscuous. This promiscuity is present in all regions except Iceland, where monogamy is more common. Keep in mind that I have read a few different things on the promiscuity of arctic foxes. Wikipedia claims they are promiscuous and that’s what I have written down. While another source claims that they are completely monogamous. With one non-breeding vixen from the previous year staying with the family to help raise the kits. Multiple sources also say that they are monogamous and usually mate for life.

Mating season spans from April to May. They have liters of about 5-9, but they can (very rarely) have as much as 14 to 25 kits. The most of any canine.

They are one of the most common foxes in fur farms. They are bred to be “loose-skinned”, which produces bigger coats of fur. Which is why the coats of captive arctic foxes tend to be much larger than their wild counterpart. Although fur farms have been going downhill since the end of the 20th century. They are more submissive compared to red foxes, and they tend to get along better with other foxes.
